  "prompt": "What is the difference between '-' and '-=' operators in C++?",
  "response": "In C++, the `-` and `-=` operators are used for different purposes, primarily in the context of arithmetic operations.\n\n1. **`-` (Subtraction Operator)**:\n   - The `-` operator is the standard subtraction operator. It is used to perform subtraction between two operands.\n   - This operator does not alter the original value of the operands; instead, it produces a new value that is the result of the subtraction.\n   - Example:\n     ```cpp\n     int a = 10;\n     int b = 5;\n     int c = a - b; // c will be 5, a remains 10, and b remains 5\n     ```\n\n2. **`-=` (Subtraction Assignment Operator)**:\n   - The `-=` operator is a compound assignment operator. It subtracts the right operand from the left operand and then assigns the result to the left operand.\n   - This operator modifies the value of the left operand directly.\n   - Example:\n     ```cpp\n     int a = 10;\n     int b = 5;\n     a -= b; // Now a will be 5, which is 10 - 5; b remains 5\n     ```\n\n### Summary\n- The `-` operator performs subtraction and returns a new result without changing the operands.\n- The `-=` operator performs subtraction and updates the left operand with the result of the operation, effectively changing its value.\n\nKeep in mind that both operations can be used in various contexts, including with different data types, but the core principle of how they function remains the same.",
